<TITLE> McCullum forearm not broken </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 LONDON, May 20 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - New Zealand wicketkeeper Brendon McCullum retired hurt after a blow to his left forearm on the final day of the first test against England at Lord's on Monday but an X-ray revealed there had been no break. McCullum was taken to hospital after he was struck on the arm by a lifting delivery from Stuart Broad as his team struggled to save the match. He was on 11 at the time after top-scoring with a run-a-ball 97 in the first innings. A spokesman for the New Zealand team said McCullum had returned to the changing room but no decision had yet been made on whether he would bat again
